node.text:
Photo by Juan Carlos Osorio @juancosoriophotography / This is an image of the partial solar eclipse that occurred during the June 10, 2021, sunrise. When the moon, sun, and Earth align perfectly, the moon casts a round shadow on our planet and the sun becomes a "ring of fire." Whether or not this phenomenon is visible depends on the exact viewing location. For New York City, this time it was seen as a partial eclipse. In several ancient cultures, eclipses have been associated with ominous events. Regardless of the amount of coverage or the interpretation of its meaning, this is a surreal sight.
Looking directly at the sun can cause irreversible damage to the eyes. Eclipse viewing should only be done with special solar filters, or in my case, with the aid of a mirrorless camera in which the sensor captures the view and converts it into a digital  image projected onto a screen.
Canon EOS R5 camera, Canon RF 800mm lens, f/11, auto ISO, aperture priority. For more images and videos of the sun, the moon, wildlife, and travel, visit @juancosoriophotography. #YourShotPhotographer #solareclipse #eclipse #sun #moon

node.text:
Photo by @ivan_lesica / While walking around Accord, New York, I noticed a tree with some decomposing leaves. I found the contrast between the dried brown sections and bright green sections quite mesmerizing. As I was deciding which leaf to photograph, I saw the shadow of a little bug on one of them and decided that was the one. I also really liked the patterns created by the intricate veins. 
SONY HX400V, f/3.5, 9.53mm, 1/1600s, ISO 80. #YourShotPhotographer #macro #leaf #patterns #nature

Nikon D810, 70-200mm, 1/250, f/2.8, ISO 220. #YourShotPhotographer

node.text: Photo by @veronika_k_ko / The hydrangea is one of my favorite flowers, and I own a few kinds: blue-purple and pink. This is a close-up of one of them taken with my mobile phone. I love how so many shades of blue and purple merge in one flower head. I like to watch and enjoy them! These are the little things that bring us joy and make us happy. #YourShotPhotographer #hydrangeas #purple #fineartphotography #beauty

Photo by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa / Shooting in black and white can highlight lines, shapes, forms, textures, contrast, and tones and give a different scale or depth to the image. Sometimes the rich tones create a mood that can be interpreted by the viewers. The joy of new discoveries with black-and-white photography inspires me deeply, and I feel a soulful connection with my images. #YourShotPhotographer
#blackandwhite #india

node.text: Photo by @celestesloman // Sponsored by @century21 // National Geographic Explorer Rae Wynn-Grant, Ph.D., a large carnivore ecologist, styles her daughter Zuri's hair as part of their morning routine before breakfast. During the pandemic Rae has been able to spend more time with her daughters since their new home is closer to her field locations. Zuri loves science and nature and grows plants, stargazes, and studies bugs with Rae in their backyard. // Home can be our sanctuary and has long been a symbol of security and safety. We've all spent more time in our homes this past year—maybe more than we had ever imagined. How has your relationship evolved with your own home as a result? Whether you live in a studio apartment in an urban high-rise, a suburban sanctuary with a fenced backyard, or someplace in between, we want to see your stories of home. Upload your images to your feed, tag @natgeoyourshot, and use #StoriesofHomeChallenge. I'll be curating submissions and featuring my favorites on the Your Shot account! // By posting with this hashtag, you agree to Nat Geo’s Terms of Use at natgeo.com/future-of-home, and that your photo does not infringe any third party’s rights.

Photo by @marc_henauer / This large male sang at 20 meters (66 feet) deep and rose to the surface every 20 minutes to breathe. The sound was so powerful that I could feel the vibrations going through my body. I photographed this specimen in the Kingdom of Tonga in the Pacific Ocean. 
Canon 5D Mark II in a Subal underwater housing, 16mm, f/10, 1/125s, ISO 400, natural light. #HumpbackWhale #Tonga #Underwater #YourShotPhotographer

node.text:
Photo by Jenny Wong @jdubcaptures / Nothing in the north ever really leaves. The stories and legends of what once was litter the taiga, an outdoor exhibit that's forever evolving. This is the depth, charm, and richness of Churchill that has captured my heart. 
The Commando cargo plane known as Miss Piggy was widely used in World War II. It was repurposed for commercial use and found its final resting place in Churchill in 1979. Because of mechanical issues after takeoff, the plane made an emergency landing in the rough taiga, causing irreparable damage to the plane and slight injury to the three crew members. Today it sits as a piece of the landscape and history of the town, ever evolving as artists adorn it with murals. #YourShotPhotographer #Manitoba
